@wenbozhu 
@ejona86 
@ctiller 

For 
"Response status encoded as part of the response body
Key-value pairs formatted as HTTP/1.1 headers block (without the empty newline \r\n to terminate the block)"

Why the HTTP format rather than HTTP2 literal format which would be faster to parse. We can also allow binary headers here without specific encoding. 

FYI the earlier description of HTTP/1.1 formatted headers seems like it is in conflict with

"For binary trailers, when the content-type is set to application/grpc-web-text, the extra base64 encoding specified in gRPC over HTTP2 for binary custom metadata is skipped."

as binary value strings can collide with header delimiters.

@lhecker  Thanks for the feedback!

The grpc-web spec introduces minimum changes to the existing grpc over HTTP/2 protocol. The new spec itself is bidi ready, while the actual bidi support is subject to environment/platform/network constraints (same for the grpc or WebSocket, as you noted).

How about we open a separate issue to discuss how to support bidi streams with grpc-web clients, after this spec has been reviewed and implemented? Your contribution in this work or any future work to support bidi streams is more than welcomed.  @zinuga
